passages.text: Ulta reports comp acceleration and market share gains, management still sounds conservative
ULTA12m Price Target: $584.00Price: $530.63Upside: 10.1%

Following ULTA's 2Q earnings beat, the stock was trading up \(\sim 4\%\) after market. ULTA updated its FY25 guidance, including higher top line, operating margin, and EPS expectations at the midpoint. Our key takeaways from the call include: 1) ULTA increased FY25 comp expectations following a 2Q top line beat; 2) the company now expects higher SG&A growth for the year, while FY25 operating margin guidance increased; and 3) ULTA's higher EPS supports the higher stock price.

We think Ulta's comp acceleration is being fueled by a healthy cosmetics category and strong company execution, with the company's investment in marketing, labor and service resulting in market share gains. While most retailers face a more uncertain environment in the 2H due to the prospect of higher prices across retail, we think management's FY25 top line guidance will prove to be conservative given this momentum in the business. We reiterate our Buy rating on ULTA with an updated price target of \(\) 584\$

ULTA increased FY25 comp expectations following a 2Q top line beat: ULTA reported SSS of \(+6.7\%\) , compared to consensus (LSEG Data & Analytics) of \(+2.9\%\) , driven by higher ticket \((+2.9\%)\) and transactions \((+3.7\%)\) . By category, fragrance was the strongest, delivering robust \(+\) DD comp growth. Skin care and wellness came in at \(+\) HSD, while the hair category delivered \(+\) M$D comps. Makeup came in at \(+\) MSD, versus a slight decrease in 1Q, with a positive performance in both mass and prestige makeup. Of note, ULTA saw market share gains in both mass and prestige. reflect a strong 1H performance along with the impact of Space NK, which was not contemplated previously. We the company increased its sales expectations for 2H, management continued to take a cautious approach given ongoing uncertainty around consumer spending within its FY25 guidance, ULTA now expects a comp in the \(+2.5\%\) to \(3.5\%\) range \((vS10\%\) to \(1.5\%\) prior), which reflects expectations that 2H comps will in the range of flat to \(+LSD\) , a deceleration on a one and two year stack, which appears conservative, even if the 2H macro environment were to get tougher.

SG&A growth expectations are now higher for the year: The company increased SG&A growth guidance for the year to \(+13 - 14\%\) , versus March guidance to \(+10\%\) . Per management, this is driven primarily by the company's strategic investments and advertising, as well as increased store payroll and benefits. Elevated SG&A growth in 2H will reflect both the shift of investment spending initially planned for 1H, along with lapping last year's expense trend \((SG\& A + 1\%\) in 2H24). That said, ULTA increased its FY25 operating margin guidance to \(11.9 - 12.0\%\) , versus \(11.7 - 11.8\%\) prior, while it expects to see a 2H operating margin of \(10.7 - 10.9\%\) , reflecting updated sales expectations, higher incentive comp, and the anticipated flow of investment spend.

ULTA's higher EPS supports the higher stock price: ULTA is now guiding to FY25 EPS of \(23.85 - 24.30\) (vs. \(22.65 - 23.20\) prior), up \(5\%\) at the midpoint. Looking ahead, our FY25 estimate increases \(- 2\%\) , while our FY26 EPS estimate increases \(- 6\%\) . While ULTA is currently trading at \(- 21x\) NTM PE, we would highlight that a higher EPS for this year and next year should drive further stock upside.

ULTA reported 2Q EPS of \(5.78\) , above GS/consensus (LSEG Data & Analytics) of \(5.11 / 5.08\) , and compared to \(5.30\) reported a year ago. SSS of \(+6.7\%\) tracked above consensus of \(+2.9\%\) , driven by higher ticket \((+2.9\%)\) and transactions \((+3.7\%)\) . Gross margin of \(39.2\%\) increased 82 bps y/y, largely due to lower inventory shrink and higher merchandise margin, partially offset by deleverage of supply chain costs and other revenue. The SG&A rate of \(26.6\%\) increased by 130 bps y/y, primarily due to higher incentive compensation, store payroll and benefits, and corporate overhead. Operating margin came in at \(12.4\%\) , above GS/consensus of \(11.3\% /11.6\%\) .

Our FY25 EPS estimate increases to \(24.31\) from \(23.76\) . Additionally, our FY26/FY27 EPS estimates increase \(+6.1\% / + 9.0\%\) to \(27.25 / \$ 30.42\) , respectively.

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.
